The World Health Organization announced on 11 February 2020 that the official name of the disease was "COVID-19".
The head of WHO, Tedros Adhanon Ghebreyesus, explained that "CO" is "corona", "VI", "virus", "D", and "19" is from when the outbreak was identified: December 31, 2019.
The name was chosen to avoid references to a specific geographic location (e.g.: China), animal species or group of people, in accordance with international recommendations to prevent stigmatizations. The virus that causes COVID-19 was called a severe acute respiratory syndrome virus 2 (SARS-CoV-2).
WHO also uses "COVID-19" and "COVID-19" virus in communication to the public.
Both disease and virus are commonly referred to as coronavirus.
During the initial outbreak in Wuhan, China, the virus and disease were commonly called "coronavirus" and "Wuh coronavirus".
In January 2020, WHO recommended "2019-nCov" and "acute respiratory disease for 2019-nCov" as interim names for the virus and disease, according to the 2015 guidance against the use of sites in disease and virus names.
The official names COVID-19 and SARS-CoV-2 were published on February 11, 2020.
